1
00:00:01,400 --> 00:00:06,225
The k-means algorithm requires
as one of its inputs, k,

2
00:00:06,225 --> 00:00:08,790
the number of clusters
you want it to find,

3
00:00:08,790 --> 00:00:11,820
but how do you decide how
many clusters to used.

4
00:00:11,820 --> 00:00:13,770
Do you want two clusters
or three clusters of

5
00:00:13,770 --> 00:00:16,785
five clusters or 10
clusters? Let's take a look.

6
00:00:16,785 --> 00:00:18,990
For a lot of
clustering problems,

7
00:00:18,990 --> 00:00:23,655
the right value of K
is truly ambiguous.

8
00:00:23,655 --> 00:00:25,650
If I were to show

9
00:00:25,650 --> 00:00:28,230
different people the
same data set and ask,

10
00:00:28,230 --> 00:00:30,390
how many clusters do you see?

11
00:00:30,390 --> 00:00:33,360
There will definitely be
people that will say,

12
00:00:33,360 --> 00:00:36,515
it looks like there are
two distinct clusters

13
00:00:36,515 --> 00:00:38,530
and they will be right.

14
00:00:38,530 --> 00:00:42,030
There would also be
others that will see

15
00:00:42,030 --> 00:00:47,085
actually four distinct clusters.

16
00:00:47,085 --> 00:00:49,710
They would also be right.

17
00:00:49,710 --> 00:00:51,995
Because clustering is

18
00:00:51,995 --> 00:00:55,415
unsupervised learning
algorithm you're not given

19
00:00:55,415 --> 00:00:58,100
the quote right
answers in the form

20
00:00:58,100 --> 00:01:01,445
of specific labels
to try to replicate.

21
00:01:01,445 --> 00:01:05,690
There are lots of applications
where the data itself

22
00:01:05,690 --> 00:01:08,030
does not give a clear indicator

23
00:01:08,030 --> 00:01:10,495
for how many clusters
there are in it.

24
00:01:10,495 --> 00:01:12,920
I think it truly is ambiguous if

25
00:01:12,920 --> 00:01:15,530
this data has two or four,

26
00:01:15,530 --> 00:01:18,170
or maybe three clusters.

27
00:01:18,170 --> 00:01:20,060
If you take say, the red one

28
00:01:20,060 --> 00:01:22,340
here and the two
blue ones here say.

29
00:01:22,340 --> 00:01:25,820
If you look at the academic
literature on K-means,

30
00:01:25,820 --> 00:01:29,450
there are a few techniques
to try to automatically

31
00:01:29,450 --> 00:01:31,160
choose the number of

32
00:01:31,160 --> 00:01:34,100
clusters to use for a
certain application.

33
00:01:34,100 --> 00:01:36,200
I'll briefly mention one here

34
00:01:36,200 --> 00:01:38,735
that you may see
others refer to,

35
00:01:38,735 --> 00:01:40,085
although I had to say,

36
00:01:40,085 --> 00:01:44,845
I personally do not use
this method myself.

37
00:01:44,845 --> 00:01:48,485
But one way to try to
choose the value of K

38
00:01:48,485 --> 00:01:52,280
is called the elbow method and

39
00:01:52,280 --> 00:01:54,800
what that does is you would run

40
00:01:54,800 --> 00:01:58,850
K-means with a
variety of values of

41
00:01:58,850 --> 00:02:01,700
K and plot the cost function or

42
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:03,875
the distortion function J

43
00:02:03,875 --> 00:02:06,430
as a function of the
number of clusters.

44
00:02:06,430 --> 00:02:08,660
What you find is
that when you have

45
00:02:08,660 --> 00:02:11,390
very few clusters,
say one cluster,

46
00:02:11,390 --> 00:02:14,070
the distortion function or
the cost function J will be

47
00:02:14,070 --> 00:02:17,705
high and as you increase
the number of clusters,

48
00:02:17,705 --> 00:02:22,785
it will go down,
maybe as follows.

49
00:02:22,785 --> 00:02:24,595
and if the curve looks like this,

50
00:02:24,595 --> 00:02:26,350
you say, well, it looks

51
00:02:26,350 --> 00:02:28,300
like the cost function
is decreasing

52
00:02:28,300 --> 00:02:30,610
rapidly until we get
to three clusters

53
00:02:30,610 --> 00:02:33,340
but the decrease is
more slowly after that.

54
00:02:33,340 --> 00:02:35,410
Let's choose K equals

55
00:02:35,410 --> 00:02:38,680
3 and this is called
an elbow, by the way,

56
00:02:38,680 --> 00:02:41,980
because think of it as analogous

57
00:02:41,980 --> 00:02:47,360
to that's your hand and
that's your elbow over here.

58
00:02:47,810 --> 00:02:50,340
Plotting the cost function as

59
00:02:50,340 --> 00:02:51,890
a function of K could help,

60
00:02:51,890 --> 00:02:53,340
it could help you
gain some insight.

61
00:02:53,340 --> 00:02:56,040
I personally hardly ever

62
00:02:56,040 --> 00:02:58,170
use the the elbow
method myself to

63
00:02:58,170 --> 00:03:00,205
choose the right
number of clusters

64
00:03:00,205 --> 00:03:02,745
because I think for a
lot of applications,

65
00:03:02,745 --> 00:03:04,950
the right number of
clusters is truly

66
00:03:04,950 --> 00:03:07,380
ambiguous and you
find that a lot of

67
00:03:07,380 --> 00:03:10,230
cost functions look
like this with

68
00:03:10,230 --> 00:03:13,460
just decreases smoothly and it

69
00:03:13,460 --> 00:03:16,650
doesn't have a clear
elbow by wish you

70
00:03:16,650 --> 00:03:19,995
could use to pick the
value of K. By the way,

71
00:03:19,995 --> 00:03:22,725
one technique that does
not work is to choose

72
00:03:22,725 --> 00:03:25,860
K so as to minimize
the cost function

73
00:03:25,860 --> 00:03:27,990
J because doing so

74
00:03:27,990 --> 00:03:30,330
would cause you to almost
always just choose

75
00:03:30,330 --> 00:03:33,720
the largest possible
value of K because having

76
00:03:33,720 --> 00:03:35,520
more clusters will pretty much

77
00:03:35,520 --> 00:03:38,185
always reduce the
cost function J.

78
00:03:38,185 --> 00:03:40,590
Choosing K to minimize

79
00:03:40,590 --> 00:03:43,320
the cost function J is
not a good technique.

80
00:03:43,320 --> 00:03:47,075
How do you choose the
value of K and practice?

81
00:03:47,075 --> 00:03:51,100
Often you're running K-means
in order to get clusters

82
00:03:51,100 --> 00:03:54,910
to use for some later or
some downstream purpose.

83
00:03:54,910 --> 00:03:57,190
That is, you're going to
take the clusters and do

84
00:03:57,190 --> 00:03:59,830
something with those clusters.

85
00:03:59,830 --> 00:04:02,440
What I usually do and
what I recommend you

86
00:04:02,440 --> 00:04:05,050
do is to evaluate K-means

87
00:04:05,050 --> 00:04:07,540
based on how well it performs

88
00:04:07,540 --> 00:04:11,010
for that later
downstream purpose.

89
00:04:11,010 --> 00:04:15,160
Let me illustrate to the
example of t-shirt sizing.

90
00:04:15,160 --> 00:04:18,100
One thing you could
do is run K-means

91
00:04:18,100 --> 00:04:20,785
on this data set to
find the clusters,

92
00:04:20,785 --> 00:04:23,810
in which case you
may find clusters

93
00:04:23,810 --> 00:04:27,205
like that and this would be
how you size your small,

94
00:04:27,205 --> 00:04:29,470
medium, and large t-shirts,

95
00:04:29,470 --> 00:04:32,620
but how many t-shirt
sizes should there be?

96
00:04:32,620 --> 00:04:34,300
Well, it's ambiguous.

97
00:04:34,300 --> 00:04:38,725
If you were to also run
K-means with five clusters,

98
00:04:38,725 --> 00:04:43,670
you might get clusters
that look like this.

99
00:04:43,670 --> 00:04:45,320
This will let shoe size

100
00:04:45,320 --> 00:04:47,380
t-shirts according
to extra small,

101
00:04:47,380 --> 00:04:51,280
small, medium, large,
and extra large.

102
00:04:51,280 --> 00:04:53,590
Both of these are
completely valid

103
00:04:53,590 --> 00:04:56,200
and completely fine groupings

104
00:04:56,200 --> 00:04:58,205
of the data into clusters,

105
00:04:58,205 --> 00:05:00,175
but whether you want to use

106
00:05:00,175 --> 00:05:03,250
three clusters or
five clusters can

107
00:05:03,250 --> 00:05:05,560
now be decided
based on what makes

108
00:05:05,560 --> 00:05:08,515
sense for your t-shirt business.

109
00:05:08,515 --> 00:05:11,725
Does a trade-off between how
well the t-shirts will fit,

110
00:05:11,725 --> 00:05:15,760
depending on whether you have
three sizes or five sizes,

111
00:05:15,760 --> 00:05:19,750
but there will be extra costs
as well associated with

112
00:05:19,750 --> 00:05:22,180
manufacturing and
shipping five types of

113
00:05:22,180 --> 00:05:25,420
t-shirts instead of three
different types of t-shirts.

114
00:05:25,420 --> 00:05:27,850
What I would do in
this case is to run

115
00:05:27,850 --> 00:05:31,260
K-means with K equals
3 and K equals 5

116
00:05:31,260 --> 00:05:35,350
and then look at these
two solutions to

117
00:05:35,350 --> 00:05:37,480
see based on the trade-off

118
00:05:37,480 --> 00:05:40,660
between fits of t-shirts
with more sizes,

119
00:05:40,660 --> 00:05:42,969
results in better fit versus

120
00:05:42,969 --> 00:05:46,450
the extra cost of making
more t-shirts where making

121
00:05:46,450 --> 00:05:49,380
fewer t-shirts is simpler
and less expensive to

122
00:05:49,380 --> 00:05:52,755
try to decide what makes sense
for the t-shirt business.

123
00:05:52,755 --> 00:05:55,665
When you get to the
programming exercise,

124
00:05:55,665 --> 00:05:58,305
you also see there
an application

125
00:05:58,305 --> 00:06:01,320
of K-means to image compression.

126
00:06:01,320 --> 00:06:04,710
This is actually one of the
most fun visual examples

127
00:06:04,710 --> 00:06:05,835
of K-means and there

128
00:06:05,835 --> 00:06:07,940
you see that there'll
be a trade-off

129
00:06:07,940 --> 00:06:10,000
between the quality of
the compressed image,

130
00:06:11,130 --> 00:06:13,835
that is, how good
the image looks

131
00:06:13,835 --> 00:06:16,195
versus how much you can
compress the image

132
00:06:16,195 --> 00:06:17,370
to save the space.

133
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,265
In that program exercise,

134
00:06:20,265 --> 00:06:21,900
you see that you can use

135
00:06:21,900 --> 00:06:25,320
that trade-off to maybe
manually decide what's

136
00:06:25,320 --> 00:06:26,760
the best value of K

137
00:06:26,760 --> 00:06:28,530
based on how good do
you want the image to

138
00:06:28,530 --> 00:06:31,110
look versus how large

139
00:06:31,110 --> 00:06:33,740
you want the compress
image size to be.

140
00:06:33,740 --> 00:06:37,875
That's it for the K-means
clustering algorithm.

141
00:06:37,875 --> 00:06:39,255
Congrats on learning

142
00:06:39,255 --> 00:06:41,680
your first unsupervised
learning algorithm.

143
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:44,550
You now know not just how
to do supervised learning,

144
00:06:44,550 --> 00:06:46,790
but also unsupervised learning.

145
00:06:46,790 --> 00:06:50,025
I hope you also have fun
with the practice lab,

146
00:06:50,025 --> 00:06:52,290
is actually one of the
most fun exercises

147
00:06:52,290 --> 00:06:54,935
I know of the K-means.

148
00:06:54,935 --> 00:06:57,795
With that, we're
ready to move on to

149
00:06:57,795 --> 00:07:00,915
our second unsupervised
learning algorithm,

150
00:07:00,915 --> 00:07:03,030
which is a non-linear detection.

151
00:07:03,030 --> 00:07:05,055
How do you look at
the data set and find

152
00:07:05,055 --> 00:07:08,010
unusual or anomalous
things in it.

153
00:07:08,010 --> 00:07:10,155
This turns out to be another,

154
00:07:10,155 --> 00:07:12,960
one of the most commercially
important applications

155
00:07:12,960 --> 00:07:14,400
of unsupervised learning.

156
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:15,900
I've used this myself many

157
00:07:15,900 --> 00:07:17,940
times in many different
applications.

158
